---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  pageTitle="See rough thinking become review-ready"
  seoTitle="WordPresto workflow demo — editorial and search intelligence in one workflow"
  description="A writer's rough notes move through WordPresto. Editorial brief, search intent, structure, voice, review, metadata and CMS handoff — without handing judgement to a machine."
  canonical="https://wordpresto.com/workflow-demo/"
  noindex={true}
>

  <!-- ===================== MASTHEAD ===================== -->
  <header class="masthead">
    <div class="masthead-inner">
      <nav class="masthead-nav masthead-nav--left">
        <a href="/waitlist" class="nav-link">Sign in</a>
        <a href="/#product" class="nav-link">Product</a>
        <a href="/workers/" class="nav-link">Workers</a>
      </nav>
      <a href="/" class="masthead-logo">
        <img src="/brand/main-logo.png" alt="Word Presto — the content engine behind publishing" height="110" />
      </a>
      <nav class="masthead-nav masthead-nav--right">
        <a href="/#use-cases" class="nav-link">Use cases</a>
        <a href="/workers/" class="nav-link">Workers</a>
        <a href="/waitlist" class="btn btn--primary btn--sm">Join the waitlist</a>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ===================== INTRO ===================== -->
  <section class="section section--intro">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="eyebrow eyebrow--demo">Workflow demo</div>
      <h1 class="demo-h1">See rough thinking become review-ready.</h1>
      <p class="demo-intro">A writer's rough notes move through WordPresto. Brief, structure, voice, review and approval — without handing judgement to a machine.</p>
      <p class="demo-note">Follow the steps below. Each one reveals a stage of the content workflow. Nothing is published at the end — human approval is required first.</p>
      <div class="track-legend">
        <span class="track-legend-item"><span class="track-dot track-dot--editorial"></span>Editorial track</span>
        <span class="track-legend-item"><span class="track-dot track-dot--search"></span>Search intelligence track</span>
        <span class="track-legend-item"><span class="track-dot track-dot--handoff"></span>Handoff track</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===================== DEMO AREA ===================== -->
  <section class="section section--demo section--border-top">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Progress rail -->
      <div class="progress-rail" aria-label="Workflow progress" role="progressbar" aria-valuemin={0} aria-valuemax={15} aria-valuenow={0}>
        <div class="progress-rail-inner">
          {Array.from({ length: 16 }, (_, i) => (
            <span class={`progress-dot${i === 0 ? ' progress-dot--active' : ''}`} data-step={i} aria-label={`Step ${i}`}></span>
          ))}
        </div>
        <span class="progress-label mono-label">Step <span id="progress-current">0</span> of 15</span>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 0: Writer Primer ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step demo-step--visible" id="step-0" data-step="0">
        <div class="step-label mono-label">YOUR NOTES · CLINIC WEBSITE ARTICLE · IN PROGRESS</div>
        <div class="primer-card">
          <div class="primer-margin"></div>
          <div class="primer-body">

            <p class="primer-line primer-line--lead">Why aesthetic clinic websites often fail after launch — even when the design looks polished.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">I want to write about why the website often fails not because the design is wrong, but because the clinic workflow behind it is undefined. The design can look professional and still lose every enquiry because nobody has decided what happens when the message comes in, who it goes to, what a suitable lead actually looks like, or what the patient is supposed to do after they land on the page.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">I don't want this to sound like I'm attacking designers. Good design matters. The point is that design cannot fix an undefined workflow — and that's the clinic's job to sort out first, not the agency's.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line primer-line--keep">Keep the phrase: "the website is not the workflow."</p>
            <span class="hand-annot hand-annot--keep">keep this ↓</span>
            <p class="primer-line primer-line--keep">Possibly also: "a form is not a follow-up system."</p>
            <p class="primer-line">The first phrase is the core idea. The second might be the best single line in the whole piece. Not sure whether to use both or just one — writer decision, not the brief's.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Pain points I want to cover (from real patterns, not invented):</p>
            <p class="primer-line">— WhatsApp enquiries that arrive with no owner — they sit on the clinic manager's phone, sometimes for days, with no handover system<br />
            — Contact forms that collect vague enquiries but no qualification data: no treatment type, no timeline, no sense of whether this is the right patient<br />
            — People booking consultations before anyone has checked suitability — wasted appointments, disappointed patients, staff time lost<br />
            — Staff replying to enquiries in completely different tones depending on who is on shift<br />
            — Clinic owners asking agencies for a better website when the actual problem is the intake process<br />
            — Consent starting at the wrong point — often after the booking, sometimes after the treatment begins<br />
            — Aftercare and follow-up living in a separate system with no connection back to the original enquiry<br />
            — Clinic owners diagnosing a conversion problem when they actually have a workflow problem</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Audience: clinic owners, clinic managers, and possibly agencies who build clinic sites. The tone should be fair to agencies. An agency cannot design around a workflow the clinic hasn't defined. That's the clinic's responsibility first.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">Tone: experienced, fair, practical. Not a lecture. Not another "here is what a great website looks like" piece. No "unlock your digital potential" energy. Domain knowledge, not generic content-marketing voice.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Claims caution: do not say "most clinic websites fail" without defining what failure means. Failure here means the site does not create a clear, qualified next step for the right kind of patient. Use scenarios rather than statistics.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">Consent and aftercare references should stay operational. Do not stray into legal or compliance advice — that is not this piece.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Format question — I am not sure what this should become:<br />
            1. An article (probably first)<br />
            2. A landing page section for a service offering<br />
            3. A guide for clinic owners to work through before briefing a website project<br /><br />
            Start as an article. It could feed a service page later. Decision deferred until first draft is shaped.</p>

          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="1">Shape this thinking →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 1: Omar — Content Analyst (EDITORIAL) ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-1" data-step="1">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 1 OF 15 · OMAR · CONTENT ANALYST · EDITORIAL TRACK</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Reading your notes. Extracting what matters before a brief is written. Flagging signals that will feed search intelligence.</p>
        <div class="output-card">
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">CONTENT ANALYSIS</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Core argument</div>
              <p class="output-para">The clinic website fails not because the design is wrong, but because the workflow behind it was never defined. Design cannot fix an undefined operational process. That is the clinic's responsibility — not the agency's.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Audience groups identified</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Primary: clinic owners commissioning or reviewing a website<br />— Secondary: clinic managers who handle day-to-day enquiries<br />— Adjacent: agencies who build clinic sites (this audience changes the tone requirement)<br /><span class="output-indent">→ Writer's note explicitly asks that agencies not be blamed. Brief must carry this.</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Two phrases to preserve — both flagged by writer</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "the website is not the workflow" — core thesis, use as section anchor<br />— "a form is not a follow-up system" — strongest single line in notes; writer uncertain whether to use both<br /><span class="output-indent">Recommendation: keep both. They do different things. First is the argument; second is the best example of it.</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Tension to manage</div>
              <p class="output-para">Writer wants to be fair to agencies. The risk is that the piece reads as "agencies make nice pages and miss the point." That reading alienates a legitimate audience and misattributes blame. The brief should make explicit: the clinic is responsible for defining the workflow before briefing a designer.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Claims risk areas</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "Most clinics don't have a system" — unquantified. Use scenarios, not statistics.<br />— Consent and aftercare references must stay operational. No legal framing.<br />— Avoid "most agencies" language — see tension note above.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Signals passing to search intelligence</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Core topic: aesthetic clinic website readiness before design brief<br />— Reader pain: clinic owner whose site isn't generating qualified enquiries<br />— Writer's domain advantage: operational depth — no competitor content covers intake workflow this specifically<br />— Format signal: article first; potential for pre-brief guide format downstream</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="voice-note">
            <span class="hand-note">Two phrases, not one. Both should reach the brief. Search intelligence running in parallel.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="2">Follow the workflow →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 2: Intent Worker (SEARCH TRACK) ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-2" data-step="2">
        <div class="worker-pill worker-pill--search mono-label">STEP 2 OF 15 · INTENT WORKER · SEARCH INTELLIGENCE TRACK</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Mapping what readers are actually searching for. Search intent supports the angle. It does not replace it.</p>
        <div class="output-card output-card--search">
          <div class="output-card-header output-card-header--ruled">
            <span class="output-card-title">SEARCH INTENT ANALYSIS</span>
            <span class="track-badge track-badge--search">SEARCH TRACK</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Primary intent identified</div>
              <p class="output-para">Frustrated clinic owner, likely about to commission a website rebuild, searching to understand why their current site isn't generating enquiries. The reader has already identified a problem — they are looking for a frame to understand it, not a list of generic improvements.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Query family</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "why isn't my clinic website getting enquiries"<br />— "aesthetic clinic website not converting"<br />— "clinic website before and after results but no bookings"<br />— "what to fix before redesigning clinic website"<br />— "clinic website brief checklist"<br />— "aesthetic clinic intake process"</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Reader journey stage</div>
              <p class="output-para">Problem-aware, solution-unaware. The reader knows something is wrong but has not yet named the problem correctly. They are attributing the failure to the website. The writer's argument — that the failure is actually a workflow failure — is exactly what this reader needs. The article reframes their diagnosis.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Snippet opportunity</div>
              <p class="output-para">A direct, quotable answer in the first 200 words — "a clinic website fails not because the design is wrong, but because the intake workflow behind it was never defined" — is a strong candidate for featured snippet and People Also Ask capture. The writer's core thesis is already snippet-shaped.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">What this does not change</div>
              <p class="output-para">The writer's angle, voice and domain knowledge remain theirs. The intent map shapes where the article can reach, not what the writer argues. The writer's domain knowledge is the advantage — search intelligence shows the path to the reader who needs it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="3">Continue →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 3: Content Analyst — Search Mode (SEARCH TRACK) ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-3" data-step="3">
        <div class="worker-pill worker-pill--search mono-label">STEP 3 OF 15 · CONTENT ANALYST · SEARCH MODE · SEARCH INTELLIGENCE TRACK</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Mapping the search landscape for this topic. Identifying what competitors miss — and where the writer's depth is the advantage.</p>
        <div class="output-card output-card--search">
          <div class="output-card-header output-card-header--ruled">
            <span class="output-card-title">SEARCH LANDSCAPE ANALYSIS</span>
            <span class="track-badge track-badge--search">SEARCH TRACK</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">What currently ranks on this topic</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Generic "how to improve your clinic website" articles from web agencies<br />— "X tips for aesthetic clinic marketing" listicles — high word count, low domain depth<br />— Before/after gallery optimisation posts targeting visual search<br />— Platform-specific advice (Instagram, Google Ads, booking software)<br />— No authoritative content specifically on operational readiness before the design brief</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">The gap this writer owns</div>
              <p class="output-para">Nothing in the current search landscape covers "what a clinic must have operationally before briefing a website project." That is the exact argument in the writer's notes. The writer's domain knowledge is the advantage — not a marketing formula, but lived operational understanding of how clinics actually lose enquiries. No competitor content comes close to this specificity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Competitor content weaknesses</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Surface-level conversion advice: "add a clear CTA," "use better images"<br />— No coverage of intake workflow, follow-up systems, or enquiry ownership<br />— Agency-authored content that (predictably) positions the agency as the solution<br />— No content that reframes a "website problem" as a "workflow problem"</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">SEO checks the path — writer takes it</div>
              <p class="output-para">SEO checks the path, structure and evidence. The writer's argument is the destination. The gap analysis confirms the topic is underserved at depth. The content brief will incorporate this landscape to shape structure and evidence — not to alter the writer's argument.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="4">Continue →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 4: Cluster Worker (SEARCH TRACK) ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-4" data-step="4">
        <div class="worker-pill worker-pill--search mono-label">STEP 4 OF 15 · CLUSTER WORKER · SEARCH INTELLIGENCE TRACK</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Mapping topical fit. Identifying the content cluster this article belongs to, internal link opportunities, and cannibalisation risk.</p>
        <div class="output-card output-card--search">
          <div class="output-card-header output-card-header--ruled">
            <span class="output-card-title">TOPICAL CLUSTER MAP</span>
            <span class="track-badge track-badge--search">SEARCH TRACK</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Parent topic</div>
              <p class="output-para">Aesthetic clinic marketing strategy — specifically the operational layer that underpins it. This article sits within the broader cluster but carves out a distinct angle: pre-project workflow readiness rather than traffic generation or design optimisation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Supporting content this article could anchor</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Enquiry handling guide: "What to do when a new patient enquiry arrives"<br />— Consultation qualification checklist: "Is this the right patient for this treatment?"<br />— Pre-brief guide: "What to sort out before you brief a web agency"<br />— Staff tone guide: "How to respond consistently across channels"<br /><span class="output-indent">→ Writer noted format optionality — this article could later seed these derivative pieces</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Internal link slots identified</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Section on intake workflow → link to enquiry handling guide (if published)<br />— Agency-fairness section → link to "how to brief a web project" guide<br />— Consent section → link to operational consent checklist (if published)<br />— Conclusion → link to pre-brief checklist page</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Cannibalisation check</div>
              <p class="output-para">No cannibalisation risk detected. This article occupies a specific angle (pre-design workflow readiness) not covered by existing or planned content. The adjacent marketing articles cover different stages of the funnel. Safe to proceed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="5">Build the brief →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 5: Luca — Content Brief Builder (EDITORIAL) ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-5" data-step="5">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 5 OF 15 · LUCA · BRIEF BUILDER · EDITORIAL TRACK</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Building a structured content brief from the analysis and search intelligence. Both sources inform the brief — neither overrides the writer.</p>
        <div class="output-card output-card--brief">
          <div class="folder-tab">CONTENT BRIEF</div>
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">CONTENT BRIEF — CLINIC WEBSITE ARTICLE</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <dl class="brief-dl">
              <dt class="brief-dt">Working title</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Why aesthetic clinic websites often fail after launch — even when the design looks polished</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Format</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Article (1,800–2,200 words). Writer has noted format optionality — this could later seed a pre-brief guide and service page.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Primary reader</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Clinic owner, frustrated that their site isn't generating qualified enquiries — about to commission a rebuild. Has misdiagnosed a workflow problem as a design problem.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Core argument</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">The website fails not because the design is wrong, but because the intake workflow behind it was never defined. Design cannot fix an undefined operational process.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Tone</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Experienced, fair, practical. Domain knowledge, not content-marketing voice. Fair to agencies — the clinic owns this problem first.</dd>
            </dl>
            <hr class="brief-divider" />
            <dl class="brief-dl">
              <dt class="brief-dt">Phrases to preserve</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">"the website is not the workflow" (§4 section anchor, core thesis)<br />"a form is not a follow-up system" (§3 close, strongest single line)</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Claims guidance</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Use scenarios, not statistics. Define what "failure" means: site does not create a clear, qualified next step. Consent/aftercare: operational framing only — no legal advice.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Agency fairness</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Make explicit: the clinic is responsible for defining the workflow before briefing a designer. An agency cannot design around a process the clinic hasn't defined.</dd>
            </dl>
            <hr class="brief-divider" />
            <dl class="brief-dl">
              <dt class="brief-dt">Search context</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Reader is problem-aware, solution-unaware. The article reframes their diagnosis. No competitor covers operational readiness at this depth — writer's domain advantage is significant.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Topical cluster</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Anchor piece for aesthetic clinic marketing strategy. Can seed enquiry handling guide, consultation qualification checklist, pre-brief guide.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">Internal links</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Slots identified at: intake workflow section, agency-fairness section, consent section, conclusion. Placeholders flagged in structure step.</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="6">Check the evidence →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 6: Evidence Gap Worker (SEARCH TRACK) ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-6" data-step="6">
        <div class="worker-pill worker-pill--search mono-label">STEP 6 OF 15 · EVIDENCE GAP WORKER · SEARCH INTELLIGENCE TRACK</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Identifying claims that will need support. The writer's own experience is the primary evidence — the system flags where it needs to show.</p>
        <div class="output-card output-card--search">
          <div class="output-card-header output-card-header--ruled">
            <span class="output-card-title">EVIDENCE GAP ANALYSIS</span>
            <span class="track-badge track-badge--search">SEARCH TRACK</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Writer expertise as primary evidence</div>
              <p class="output-para">The writer's notes describe eight operational pain points from "real patterns, not invented." This is the evidence base. The article should make the experiential authority visible — not by citing statistics, but by describing scenarios with the specificity that only someone who has seen them can produce. The writer's domain knowledge is the advantage.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Claims that will need grounding</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "The website fails not because the design is wrong" — ground with a concrete scenario, not a generalisation<br />— WhatsApp enquiry pattern — describe one specific scene; the specificity earns the claim<br />— Booking before suitability check — describe the cost in practical terms (appointment wasted, staff time, patient disappointment)<br />— "Clinic owners diagnosing a conversion problem when they have a workflow problem" — this is the reframe; earn it with a before/after example</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--warning">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--warning">Caution areas (from writer's own notes)</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Do not write "most clinic websites fail" — writer has already flagged this. Use: "a clinic website can look polished and still lose every enquiry because..."<br />— Consent and aftercare: operational description only — no legal framing<br />— Agency fairness: no generalisation about agencies — the specific claim is "a clinic cannot brief what it hasn't defined"</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">What does not need external evidence</div>
              <p class="output-para">Operational descriptions — the WhatsApp pattern, the tone inconsistency, the qualification gap — are observable, not claimed statistics. Write them as scenarios. The reader's recognition is the validation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="7">Build the structure →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 7: Marcus — Structure Worker (EDITORIAL + SEARCH) ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-7" data-step="7">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 7 OF 15 · MARCUS · STRUCTURE WORKER · EDITORIAL + SEARCH</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Building the article outline. Section intent, anchor placement, FAQ candidates, internal link slots — shaped by both editorial brief and search intelligence.</p>
        <div class="output-card">
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">ARTICLE OUTLINE</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body output-card-body--outline">

            <div class="outline-row outline-row--h1">
              <span class="outline-tag">H1</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">Why aesthetic clinic websites often fail after launch — even when the design looks polished</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">Working title. Writer to finalise. Strong snippet candidate — states the reframe directly.</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section">
              <span class="outline-tag">§1</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">The scenario: a polished site that loses every enquiry</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">Open with a specific scene — not a statistic. WhatsApp enquiry with no owner is a strong opener. Earn the reframe before stating it.</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section">
              <span class="outline-tag">§2</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">What "the website fails" actually means</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">Define failure: the site does not create a clear, qualified next step for the right patient. This is the evidence-gap anchor — grounds the central claim without overstating.</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section">
              <span class="outline-tag">§3</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">Eight patterns that cause the failure — none of them design problems</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">Work through the eight pain points from the writer's notes. Scenario-first for each. Consent and aftercare: operational framing only.</span>
                <span class="outline-sub outline-text--preserved">→ Close §3 with: "a form is not a follow-up system."</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="outline-row outline-row--anchor">
              <span class="outline-tag">§4</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">The workflow the design is supposed to support</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">Section anchor: the core thesis, stated directly.</span>
