            <div class="draft-margin"></div>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--heading">Why aesthetic clinic websites often fail after launch — even when the design looks polished</p>
            <p class="draft-text">The WhatsApp message arrived at 9.47 on a Tuesday morning. A prospective patient, interested in a treatment, asking what the next step was. By Wednesday evening, it had been read and not replied to. By Friday it had been forgotten. The clinic had no system for deciding who owned an incoming enquiry. The website had generated a lead. Nobody had decided what to do with it.</p>
            <p class="draft-text">This is not a design problem. The clinic's website was well-built, well-photographed, and clearly described the treatments on offer. The design was not the failure. The workflow was.</p>

            <p class="draft-text draft-text--subheading">§3 — WHAT A FORM IS NOT</p>
            <p class="draft-text">A contact form is not a qualification system. It collects names and messages. It does not filter treatment type, patient timeline, or suitability. A clinic using a standard contact form is collecting vague intent and hoping that something useful arrives. Sometimes it does. More often it arrives alongside enquiries that were never the right fit, at volumes that make response time longer, with no structure to distinguish one from another.</p>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--anchor">A form is not a follow-up system.</p>
            <p class="draft-text">A form is the beginning of a process that the clinic needs to have defined before the form was built. If the process was not defined, the form is a decoration.</p>

            <p class="draft-text draft-text--subheading">§4 — THE WORKFLOW THE DESIGN WAS SUPPOSED TO SUPPORT</p>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--anchor">The website is not the workflow.</p>
            <p class="draft-text">The website presents the clinic. It describes the treatments, shows the environment, introduces the practitioners, and makes the phone number findable. What it cannot do is define what happens when a suitable patient responds. That is a workflow question. It requires decisions the clinic must make before briefing any designer: who owns an enquiry, what qualifies a patient, what a suitable consultation looks like, and what happens after it.</p>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--anchor-placeholder">[§5 — WHAT TO DEFINE BEFORE BRIEFING A WEB PROJECT — continues in full draft]</p>
